s and groups deployed Internet technologies to variously construct, defend, and challenge narratives of Iranian national identity, society, and politics. While it tempers celebratory claims that have dominated assessments of the Iranian Internet, Electronic Iran is ultimately optimistic in its outlook. As it exposes and assesses overlooked aspects of the Iranian Internet, the book sketches a more complete map of its dynamic landscape, and suggests that the transformative powers of digital media can only be developed and understood if attention is paid to both the specificities of new technologies as well as the local and transnational contexts in which they appear.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aInternet and activismzIran. 0aMass media and nationalismzIran. 0aOnline social networksxPolitical aspectszIran. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aIranian Internet.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831106886100 cprintz978081356193640uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9780813561943?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813561943zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813561943/original  a978-3-11-068861-0 Rutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA